/*!
    \page getting-started.html
    \title Getting started with Genesis-X

    \brief Installation, configuration, and first project setup.

    \section1 Overview

    This guide walks you through installing Genesis-X, enabling the
    modules in your Qt project, and integrating the documentation and
    tools into Qt Creator.

    By the end of this page you will have:

    \list
        \li Genesis-X installed on your system.
        \li Documentation registered in Qt Creator / Qt Assistant.
        \li A minimal project using the Genesis-X Core module.
        \li Optional: QML assets and ORM enabled.
    \endlist

    \section1 Requirements

    \list
        \li Qt 6.5 or later (Genesis-X is tested with Qt 6.9 / 6.10).
        \li Qt Creator (recommended for best integration).
        \li A supported compiler toolchain per your Qt version.
        \li CMake or qmake; Genesis-X focuses on qmake integration.
    \endlist

    \section1 Installation

    Genesis-X is distributed with an installer script:

    \list
        \li \c install.sh for Linux and macOS.
        \li \c install.bat for Windows (or \c install.sh in a bash
            environment such as Git Bash).
    \endlist

    Run the installer from a terminal:

    \code
    # Linux / macOS
    chmod +x install.sh
    ./install.sh
    \endcode

    On Windows (CMD or PowerShell):

    \code
    install.bat
    \endcode

    The installer guides you through:

    \list
        \li Installing Genesis-X libraries and headers.
        \li Installing QDoc / Qt help files.
        \li Registering documentation in Qt Creator.
        \li Installing Qt Creator snippets.
        \li Installing Qt Creator wizard templates.
        \li Optionally installing third-party integrations (for example,
            Firebase support).
    \endlist

    \section1 Qt Creator integration

    If you chose to install documentation and tools, the installer
    automatically updates Qt Creator configuration so that:

    \list
        \li Genesis-X documentation appears under
            \uicontrol {Help > Contents}.
        \li The search index includes Genesis-X types and topics.
        \li Qt Creator snippets become available for QML and C++.
        \li Wizard templates appear in
            \uicontrol {File > New Project}.
    \endlist

    If needed, you can manually add the documentation by opening:

    \list
        \li \uicontrol {Tools > Options > Help > Documentation}
        \li Click \uicontrol {Add...}
        \li Select the \c genesisx.qch file installed by Genesis-X.
    \endlist

    \section1 Adding Genesis-X to a qmake project

    To use Genesis-X in an existing qmake-based project, open the
    \c .pro file and add the required modules.

    At minimum, add the Core module:

    \code
    QT += genesisx
    \endcode

    Enable additional modules as needed:

    \code
    QT += genesisx-utils      # helpers and utilities
    QT += genesisx-orm        # ORM and HTTP controllers (optional)
    QT += genesisx-physics    # physics for View3D (optional)
    \endcode

    Then run qmake again (or trigger a reconfigure in Qt Creator) and
    rebuild the project.

    \section1 Using the QML design system (assets)

    The Genesis-X design system is shipped as a QML module, typically
    under the name \c assets.

    In your QML files:

    \code
    import QtQuick
    import QtQuick.Controls
    import assets 1.0

    ApplicationWindow {
        width: 800
        height: 600
        visible: true

        // Example usage of a design-system component
        Column {
            anchors.centerIn: parent

            AppTitle {
                text: "Hello, Genesis-X"
            }

            PrimaryButton {
                text: "Continue"
            }
        }
    }
    \endcode

    The exact components available depend on the version of the assets
    module shipped with your Genesis-X distribution. Refer to the
    \l{Genesis-X Assets}{Assets Module} documentation for the full API.

    \section1 Minimal C++ setup example

    The following example shows a minimal C++ \c main.cpp that uses
    Genesis-X alongside Qt Quick:

    \code
    #include <QGuiApplication>
    #include <QQmlApplicationEngine>

    #include <GenesisX/Core/GenesisXApplication.h>

    int main(int argc, char *argv[])
    {
        QGuiApplication app(argc, argv);

        gx::core::GenesisXApplication gxApp;
        gxApp.initialize();

        QQmlApplicationEngine engine;
        const QUrl url(u"qrc:/main.qml"_qs);

        QObject::connect(&engine, &QQmlApplicationEngine::objectCreated,
                         &app, [url](QObject *obj, const QUrl &objUrl) {
            if (!obj && url == objUrl)
                QCoreApplication::exit(-1);
        }, Qt::QueuedConnection);

        engine.load(url);

        return app.exec();
    }
    \endcode

    The exact C++ entry classes (for example \c GenesisXApplication)
    may vary depending on your installed Genesis-X version and chosen
    modules. Check the \l{Genesis-X core system}{Core Module} documentation for
    the authoritative API reference.

    \section1 Creating a new project using the wizard

    When the wizard templates are installed, you can create a new
    Genesis-X project directly from Qt Creator:

    \list 1
        \li Open Qt Creator.
        \li Select \uicontrol {File > New Project}.
        \li In the left-hand \uicontrol {Projects} tree, locate the
            \e {Genesis-X} category.
        \li Choose a Genesis-X application template (for example,
            \e {Genesis-X Quick Application}).
        \li Follow the wizard steps to configure the kit, build location,
            and project options.
    \endlist

    The generated project already contains the correct \c QT += genesisx
    entries and a minimal QML / C++ setup.

